ca 1354","1308":"1308","1329":"1329","about 1340":"circa 1340","1405":"1405","Cheshire, England":"Cheshire, England","Cubleston, Stafford, England":"Staffordshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Shocklach, Cheshire, England":"Shocklach, Cheshire, England"},"en":{"1329–1376":"1329–1376","1325–1373":"1325–1373","1325–1399":"1325–1399","1335–Male":"1335–Deceased","1327–Female":"1327–Deceased","1343–1405":"1343–1405","1360–Male":"1360–Deceased","1308–1354":"1308–1354","1311–Female":"1311–Deceased","1373":"1373","1360":"1360","1327":"1327","1325":"1325","1335":"1335","1311":"1311","1399":"1399","1376":"1376","1354":"1354","1343":"1343","about 1343":"about 1343","about 1354":"about 1354","1308":"1308","1329":"1329","about 1340":"about 1340","1405":"1405","Cheshire, England":"Cheshire, England","Cubleston, Stafford, England":"Staffordshire, England, United Kingdom","Shocklach, Cheshire, England":"Shocklach, Cheshire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Sancto","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["English: nickname from Latin  <i>sanctus</i> ‘holy, sainted’, denoting a pious person.  Compare  Saint  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Saint","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Andre, Cyr, Remy.","English and French: nickname for a particularly pious individual, from Old French and Middle English <i>saint(e)</i>, <i>seint(e)</i> ‘holy’ (from Latin <i>sanctus</i> ‘blameless, holy’). The vocabulary word was occasionally used in the Middle Ages as a personal name and this may have given rise to some instances of the surname.","English: perhaps a nickname for someone who wore, made, or sold girdles, from Middle English <i>ceint</i>, <i>seint</i>, <i>saint</i> ‘girdle’ (Old French <i>ceint</i>, Latin <i>cinctum</i>). Compare   Center  ."]}]},{"name":"Pierre","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Andre, Jacques, Antoine, Yves, Michel, Jean Claude, Mireille, Jean Robert, Francois, Monique, Raoul, Serge.","French, Walloon, West Indian (mainly Haiti), and Mauritian:","from the personal name <i>Pierre</i>, French form of   Peter   (see also below). This is one of the most frequent surnames in Haiti (along with   Jean   and   Joseph  ) and in Saint Martin. It is also established elsewhere in the West Indies (e.g. in Trinidad and Tobago, Saint Lucia, Grenada, and Bahamas)."],"variants":[{"name":"Perrault","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Armand, Gisele, Jacques, Marcel, Roch, Alphonse, Andre, Donat, Emile, Francoise, Gaston, Ghislaine.","French: from a pet form of the Old French personal name <i>Perre</i>, a variant of   Pierre  , French form of   Peter  . Compare   Paro  ,   Parro  ,   Parrow  ,   Pearo  ,   Perault  ,   Pero  ,   Perreault  ,   Perro  ,   Perrot  , and   Perrow  .","History: Jacques Perrault/Perrot <i>dit</i> Villedaigre from Mons in Charente-Maritime, France, married Michelle Le Flot in Quebec City, QC, in 1654. Nicolas Perrault/Perrot from Darcey in Côte-d’Or married Madeleine Raclos in QC in 1671. Pierre Perrault from France married Geneviève Duclos in QC <i>c.</i> 1686. François Perrault from Cosne-Cours-sur-Loire in Nièvre married Jeanne-Suzanne Pagé in Quebec City, QC, in 1715. — In North America, this surname was originally (also) a secondary surname or <i>dit</i> (‘also called’) name, borne by Louis Leparon <i>dit</i> Perrault (a son of Pierre Leparon from Derval in Loire-Atlantique, France), who married Marie-Josèphe Normandeau in Quebec City, QC, in 1751. — This surname is listed in the (US) National Huguenot Society's register of qualified Huguenot ancestors (along with its altered forms <i>Perrow</i> and <i>Pero</i>) and also in the similar registers of the Huguenot Society of America and of the Huguenot Society of the Founders of Manakin in the Colony of Virginia. The Huguenot ancestor was Charles Perrault from Bordeaux in France, one of the settlers of Manakin, VA, in the early 1700s. However, his descendants bear only altered forms of the surname, such as <i>Perrow</i> and <i>Perow</i>."]},{"name":"Perot","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Alphonse, Antoine, Philippe, Remy.","French (<b>Pérot</b>): from a pet form of the Old French personal name <i>Perre</i>, a variant of   Pierre  , French form of   Peter  . Compare   Perrow  .","Altered form of French   Perret  , a cognate of 1 above."]},{"name":"Lapierre","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Marcel, Armand, Andre, Lucien, Normand, Adrien, Alcide, Aristide, Arnaud, Julien, Pierre, Aime.","French, Walloon, and Flemish:","topographic name, with fused French feminine definite article <i>la</i>, for someone who lived on a patch of stony soil or by a large outcrop of rock, from Old French <i>pierre</i> ‘stone, rock’ (compare   Pierre   2); or a habitational name from any of various places called Lapierre or La Pierre in France and Belgium (Wallonia), with the same meaning."]},{"name":"Paret","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Andre, Philippe, Pierre.  Spanish Joaquin, Alberto, Caridad, Eduardo, Eugenio, Lourdes, Patricio, Wilfredo.","French: habitational name from (Le) Paret, the name of several places in various parts of France, ultimately derived from Latin <i>paries</i>, genitive <i>parietis</i> ‘wall’ (compare 3 below).","French: from a pet form of the personal name   Pierre  ."]},{"name":"Peregoy","meanings":["Americanized form of French <b>Périgord</b>: habitational name from Périgord, the name of a former province in France, of Gaulish origin.","Alternatively, an Americanized form of northwestern French <b>Périgois</b>, which may possibly be a cognate of 1 above, or, more likely, a regional derivative of the Old French personal name <i>Perre</i>, a variant of   Pierre  , French form of   Peter  . Compare   Pedigo  ,   Perigo  ,   Perrigo  , and   Pherigo  .","History: The progenitor of the Peregoys was Joseph Peregoy, a Frenchman who came to Baltimore County, MD, in 1685. In North America his surname was first recorded as <i>Peregois</i> and later spelled in many other ways, including <i>Perigo</i>, <i>Perigoe</i>, and <i>Perrigo</i>. The majority of his descendants (through his son Henry) bear the surname   Pedigo  ."]},{"name":"Pearre","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Andre.","Possibly also an altered form of French   Pierre  .","Altered form of English   Perry  ."]},{"name":"Peron","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Andre, Cecile, Fernand, Herve, Michel, Philippe, Virginie.","French (<b>Péron</b>): from a pet form of the Old French personal name <i>Perre</i>, a variant of   Pierre  , French form of   Peter  . Compare   Perron   1 and 2.","Breton (<b>Péron</b>, rarely <b>Le Péron</b>): variant of <b>Pédron</b> (see   Pedron  )."]},{"name":"Peter","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Hans, Kurt, Otto, Ernst, Fritz, Heinz, Helmut, Horst, Kaspar, Klaus, Siegfried, Wolfgang.","English, Scottish, German, Dutch, French (Alsace and Lorraine), Czech (Moravian), Slovak, Croatian, and Slovenian; Hungarian (<b>Péter</b>): from the personal name <i>Peter</i> (Greek <i>Petros</i>, from <i>petra</i> ‘rock’). The personal name was popular throughout Christian Europe in the Middle Ages, having been bestowed by Christ as a byname on the apostle Simon bar Jonah, the brother of Andrew. The name was chosen by Christ for its symbolic significance (John 1:42, Matt. 16:18); Saint Peter is regarded as the founding head of the Christian Church in view of Christ's saying, ‘Thou art Peter and upon this rock I will build my Church’. In Christian Germany in the early Middle Ages this was the most frequent personal name of non-ancient Germanic origin until the 14th century. In North America, this surname has also absorbed cognates from other languages, for example Czech   Petr  , Polish <b>Piotr</b> and <b>Pietr</b>, Albanian <b>Pjetri</b> (from the personal name <i>Pjetër</i>, definite form <i>Pjetri</i>), and also their derivatives (see examples at   Peterson  ). It has also been adopted as a surname by Ashkenazic Jews."]},{"name":"Perret","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Pierre, Emile, Jacques, Michel, Andree, Dominique, Etienne, Fernand, Henri, Solange.","French: from a pet form of the Old French personal name <i>Perre</i>, a variant of   Pierre  , French form of   Peter  .","English (Somerset, Gloucestershire and Wiltshire): variant of   Parrott  ."]},{"name":"Patriquin","meanings":["Altered form of French <b>Petrequin</b>: from a pet form of <i>Petre</i>, a regional variant of the personal name   Pierre   ‘Peter’."]}]},{"name":"Urian","type":"FIRST","meanings":["Danish: A husbandman"],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Urian de Sancto Pierre was born in 1329, in Shocklach, Cheshire, England, United Kingdom, his father, Sir John St Pierre, was 22 and his mother, Isabel Trussell, was 18. He married Agnes de Braose about 1340, in Cheshire, England. They were the parents of at least 1 son and 1 daughter. He died in 1376, at the age of 47."},"et":{"1329–1376":"1329–1376","1325–1373":"1325–1373","1325–1399":"1325–1399","1335–Male":"1335–Surnud","132